ing capabilities in phase 9.\n\nPhase 10 brings in recurring task scheduling with cron expressions and manual time advancement, phase 11 adds middleware and processing handlers, and phase 12 wraps everything up with a graceful shutdown mechanism.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the data structures more carefully—I need an efficient way to retrieve tasks by priority in the queue, and since this is in-memory...\n\nI'll use sorted insertion for simplicity. For task management overall, I need a Map for quick ID lookups, a sorted array for priority-then-FIFO ordering, a Set to track what's currently processing, and an array for the dead letter queue.\n\nFor the file structure, I'm going to split this into separate modules: types in one file, a cron parser in another, the main TaskQueue class handling everything, and then re-exports from the index.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the core design—I'll store all tasks in a Map keyed by ID, maintain a separate QueueState for each named queue that holds the pending task IDs in priority order, track which tasks are actively processing, and keep a dead letter queue. Dependencies will live on the task itself and get validated when pulling tasks from the queue.\n\nDefining the QueueState structure...\n\nFor the main TaskQueue class, I'll need a Map of all tasks, a Map of QueueStates indexed by queue name, a Map for schedules, and a shutdown flag to handle graceful termination.\n\nI'm going to write this myself rather than parallelize—the pieces are too tightly coupled, so I'll just work through it sequentially: types first, then the cron logic, then the main queue implementation, tests, and finally build it out.\n\nNow let me think through the actual API surface more carefully. For the basic phase, I need simple methods like adding a task, fetching the next one to process, and checking queue size. For multi-queue support, those same methods should accept an optional queue name parameter. I'm sketching out what the usage patterns should look like to make sure the implementation will support them cleanly. Writing task queue phases... I'm setting up middleware support for the task queue with the `use` method, allowing tasks to be processed through a chain of handlers before reaching the final processor. Then I'm implementing the shutdown sequence that gracefully completes remaining tasks within a timeout window and returns metrics on what was finished versus forcefully cancelled.\n\nFor the cron scheduling, I need a parser that handles the basic patterns: every N minutes with `*/N`, hourly with `0 *`, and daily at midnight with `0 0`. The core logic checks if a given timestamp matches the cron expression by evaluating each of the five fields—minute, hour, day-of-month, month, and day-of-week—where `*` matches everything, `*/N` matches when the value is divisible by N, and specific numbers match exact values.\n\nNow I'm working through the task retrieval algorithm for `getNextTask`, starting with fetching the queue state and then checking which tasks are ready to run.\n\nFor the filtering and sorting logic, I need to respect the concurrency limit first, then find pending tasks that are both available (their `availableAt` time has passed) and have all dependencies satisfied. The sorting priority is: first by priority level ascending (so 1 is highest), then by `availableAt` to handle delayed tasks in order, and finally by `createdAt` for FIFO ordering within the same priority. When scanning for the next task, I skip anything not yet available or with incomplete dependencies.\n\nI'm going to keep things simple by maintaining tasks in insertion order and scanning through them during retrieval—for typical queue sizes this is efficient enough. I'll sort by priority and creation time, then when fetching the next task, I'll scan the sorted list and return the first one that's both available and has no blocking dependencies.\n\nNow I'm setting up the project structure with separate files for types, the cron scheduler, the task queue implementation, and the main entry point, then I'll write tests and handle the build and linting.\n\nLooking at the retry logic more carefully: exponential backoff means the delay doubles with each attempt, so the first retry waits 1000ms, the second 2000ms, the third 4000ms, and once max retries are exhausted the task moves to failed status, then to a dead letter queue in phase 6. I also need to implement circular dependency detection—if task A depends on B and B depends on A, I should reject it by checking the full dependency chain.\n\nFor the later phases, progress tracking goes from 0-100 with notifications, and cancelling a task changes its status to cancelled. The tick mechanism checks all schedules against the current time and creates matching tasks. Middleware runs when tasks are processed through a pipeline where each middleware can modify the task or skip it by not calling next, and errors in middleware mark the task as failed—there's also a process method that sets up automatic queue processing with an independent middleware stack per queue.\n\nNow I'm working through how the actual processing flow connects: registering middleware with `use`, setting up handlers with `process`, and figuring out whether `process` automatically starts picking up tasks or if processing happens when `getNextTask` is called or during `tick`. about this differently. The key insight from the requirements:\n- \"Register middleware per queue\"\n- \"Task passes through all middleware in order\"\n- \"Register processing handler per queue\"\n\nI think the flow is:\n1. You add tasks with `addTask`\n2. You register middleware with `use`\n3. You register a handler with `process`\n4. When you call `getNextTask`, it returns the next task (with status 'processing')\n5. Then you need to explicitly process it... or maybe `process` starts an automatic loop?\n\nActually, I think the simplest interpretation is:\n- `process(queueName, handler)` registers a processing handler\n- When `getNextTask` is called (or perhaps there's a `processNext` method), the task goes through middleware, then the handler\n- Or maybe `process` starts automatic processing somehow\n\nLet me just implement it so that:\n\nI'm realizing the challenge here—without an event loop or external dependencies, automatic processing is difficult in an in-memory system. The cleanest approach would be to have `use()` register middleware per queue, `process()` register the handler, and then either have `getNextTask()` optionally run through the middleware chain, or create a separate `processNext()` method that handles the full pipeline. the handler. When a task is retrieved via `getNextTask()`, if there's a handler registered, the task goes through middleware + handler automatically. If no handler, `getNextTask()` just returns the task as before.\n\nI think the simplest API would be `use()` to register middleware, `process()` to register a handler and start watching the queue, and `processNext()` for explicit single-task processing. Looking at how BullMQ and Bee-Queue handle this, I want to keep it flexible for testing while still supporting automatic processing when tasks are added to a queue with a registered handler. I'm settling on a simpler design: `use()` registers middleware, `process()` registers a handler and kicks off automatic processing via setImmediate, while `getNextTask()` should also run tasks through the middleware chain rather than bypassing it entirely.\n\nActually, I need to separate concerns here—`getNextTask()` should stay synchronous for backward compatibility and just return the next task in processing status, while a new async `processNext()` method handles the full pipeline including middleware and handlers, giving tests explicit control over when tasks are processed.\n\nFor graceful shutdown, I'll need to track which tasks are actively being processed and wait for them to complete, with a timeout mechanism that force-cancels anything still running. The tricky part is that in the sync model tasks just sit in 'processing' state, but with async handlers they're actively being worked on, so shutdown needs to handle both cases by setting a flag that rejects new tasks and then waiting for in-flight operations to finish.\n\nWriting shutdown implementation... Writing the TaskQueue class... I'm validating the task addition by checking if the queue is shutting down, then extracting the queue name and priority from options with defaults, ensuring priority is a valid integer between 1 and 10. I'm also handling task dependencies by verifying each referenced task exists and checking for circular dependency chains before creating the task object.\n\nSetting up the task timing now...\n\nI'm storing the task in the map and then inserting it into the pending queue in sorted order based on priority and availability time, using a comparison function to maintain the correct sequence.\n\nNow I'm implementing the task comparison logic that orders by priority first, then by when the task becomes available, and finally by creation time for FIFO ordering. Then I'm starting to retrieve the next task from the queue while checking concurrency limits...\n\nChecking concurrency limits and iterating through pending tasks...\n\nNow I'm wrapping up the task selection logic and moving on to validate dependencies. I can see the decision point here—I was planning out how to structure this, but I'm going to stop overthinking and just write the implementation. I'll handle the core files myself and keep it consistent throughout.\n\nLet me think through the cycle detection more carefully. When adding a new task with dependencies, I need to verify those dependencies exist and check if adding it would create a circular reference. Since the new task hasn't been added yet, nothing can depend on it, so the only way a cycle forms is if one of its dependencies transitively depends back on it—but that's impossible since it doesn't exist yet. The only real